'''Voluntary Counselling and Testing''' ('''VCT''') for [[HIV]] usually involves two counseling sessions: one prior to taking the test known as "pre-test counseling" and one following the HIV test when the results are given, often referred to as "post-test counseling". Counseling focuses on the infection (HIV), the disease ([[AIDS]]), the test, and positive behavior change. VCT has become popular in many parts of [[Africa]] as a way for a person to learn their HIV status. VCT centers and counselors often use rapid HIV tests that require a drop of [[blood]] or some [[cell (biology)|cell]]s from the inside of one's cheek; the tests are cheap, require minimal training, and provide accurate results in about 15 minutes.
==External links== *[http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/vct/en/index.html World Health Organization, HIV Department Testing and Counseling page] *[http://www.unaids.org/en/Policies/Testing/default.asp UNAIDS Policy Position: HIV Testing and Counseling] *[http://www.engenderhealth.org/aids/engenderhealth-aids/response.html EngenderHealth's Response to HIV/AIDS] *[http://www.ilo.org/aids/lang--en/index.htm The International Labour Organization's programme on HIV/AIDS and the World of Work] *[http://www.ilo.org/aids/WCMS_215899/lang--en/index.htm VCT@WORK] *[http://www.plosmedicine.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.1001496 Towards Universal Voluntary HIV Testing and Counselling: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Community-Based Approache] [[Category:HIV/AIDS]] [[Category:Counseling]]
